esis of the decomposition of great masses of water?**\par \par \par [footnote]  * Compare Gay-Lussac, Sur les Volcans, in the Annales de Chimie, t. xxii., p. 427, and Bischof, W\u228\'e4rmelehre, s. 272.  The eruptions of smoke and steam which have at different periods been seen in Lancerote, Iceland, and the Kurile Islands, during the eruption of the neighboring volcanoes, afford indications of the reaction of volcanic foci through tense columns of water; that is to say, these phenomena occur when the expansive force of the vapor exceeds the hydrostatic pressure.\par \par [footnote]  ** [See Daubeney On Volcanoes, Part iii., ch. xxxvi., xxxviii., xxxix.] -- Tr.\par \par \par The discussion of these important physical questions does not come within the scope of a work of this nature; but, while we are considering these phenomena, we would enter somewhat more into the question of the geographical distribution of still active volcanoes.  We find, for instance, that in the New World, three, viz., Jorullo, Popocatepetl, and the volcano of De la Fragua, are situated at the respective distances of 80, 132, and 196 miles from the sea-coast, while in Central Asia, as Abel R\u233\'e9musat* first made known to geognosists, the Thianschan (Celestial Mountains), in which are situated the lava-emitting mountain of Pe-schan, the solfatara of Urumtsi, and the still active igneous mountain (Ho-tscheu) of Turfan, lie at an almost equal distance (1480 to 1528 miles) from the shores of the Polar Sea and those of the Indian Ocean.  \par \par \par [footnote]  *Abel R\u233\'e9musat, Lettre \u224\'e0 M. Cordier, in the Annales de Chimie, t. v., p. 137.\par \par \par Pe-schan is also fully 1360 miles distant from the Caspian Sea,* and 172 and 218 miles from the seas of Issikul and Balkasch.\par \par \par [footnote]  *Humboldt, Asie Centrale, t. ii., p. 30-33, 38-52, 70-80, and 426-428.  The existence of active volcanoes in Kordofan, 540 miles from the Red Sea, has be