masses.\par \par \par All the facts connected with our geological hypotheses on the formation of the earth's crust and the metamorphism of rocks have been unexpectedly elucidated by the ingenious idea which led to a comparison of the slags or scori\u230\'e6 of our smelting furnaces with natural minerals, and to the attempt of reproducing the latter from their elements.*\par \par \par [footnote]  *Mitscherlich, Ueber die k\u252\'fcnstliche Darstellung der Mineralien, in the Abhandl. der Akademie der Wiss. zu Berlin, 1822-3, s. 25-41.\par \par \par In all these operations, the same affinities manifest themselves which determine chemical combinations both in our laboratories and in the interior of the earth.  The most considerable part of\par p 268\par the simple minerals which characterize the more generally diffused Plutonic and erupted rocks, as well as those on which they have exercised a metamorphic action, have been produced in a crystalline state, and with perfect identify, in artificial mineral products.  We must, however, distinguish here between the scori\u230\'e6 accidentally formed, and those which have been designedly produced by chemists.  To the former belong feldspar, mica, augite, olivine, hornblende, crystallized oxyd of iron, magnetic iron in octahedral crystals, and metallis titanium;* to the latter, garnets, idocrase, rubies (equal in hardness to those found in the East), olivine, and augite.**\par \par \par [footnote]  *In scori\u230\'e6 crystals of feldspar have been discovered by Heine in the refuse of a furnace for copper fusing, near Sangerhausen, and analyzed by Kersten (Poggend., Annalen, bd. xxxiii., s. 337); crystals of augite in scori\u230\'e6 at Sahle (Mitscherlich, in the Abhandl. der Akad. zu Berlin, 1822-23, s. 40); of olivine by Seifstr\u246\'f6m (Leonhard, Basalt-Gebilde, bd. ii., s. 495); of mica in old scori\u230\'e6 of Schloss Garpenberg (Mitscherlich, in Leonhard, op. cit., s. 506); of magnetic iron in the sc